{
  "GnRH (gonadotropin-releasing hormone) is released from the:": "",
  "Anterior pituitary": "",
  "Ovary": "",
  "Hypothalamus": "",
  "Adrenal gland": "",
  "GnRH is produced and released by neuroendocrine cells of the hypothalamus in a pulsatile fashion, traveling through the hypophyseal portal system to the anterior pituitary where it stimulates the release of the gonadotropins FSH and LH.": "",
  "GnRH stimulates the anterior pituitary to release:": "",
  "ADH and oxytocin": "",
  "Testosterone and inhibin": "",
  "FSH and LH": "",
  "Estrogen and progesterone": "",
  "GnRH acts on gonadotroph cells of the anterior pituitary to stimulate the synthesis and release of the two gonadotropins: follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH), which then act on the gonads to drive reproductive function.": "",
  "In males, LH stimulates which cells and what do they produce?": "",
  "Prostate cells to release alkaline fluid": "",
  "Leydig cells to produce testosterone": "",
  "Spermatogonia to undergo meiosis directly": "",
  "Sertoli cells to produce inhibin": "",
  "In males, LH binds to receptors on Leydig (interstitial) cells located between the seminiferous tubules, stimulating them to produce testosterone. This testosterone then acts locally to support spermatogenesis and systemically to drive male secondary sex characteristics.": "",
  "In females, FSH stimulates:": "",
  "Testosterone production by the adrenal glands": "",
  "Ovarian follicle growth and estrogen production": "",
  "Ovulation directly without involving estrogen": "",
  "Progesterone production by the corpus luteum": "",
  "In females, FSH stimulates the growth and maturation of ovarian follicles during the follicular phase. The growing follicles' granulosa cells respond by producing increasing amounts of estrogen, which drives endometrial proliferation and eventually triggers the LH surge.": "",
  "Testosterone provides negative feedback to:": "",
  "Only the ovaries": "",
  "Only FSH secretion from the pituitary": "",
  "Both the hypothalamus and anterior pituitary, decreasing GnRH, FSH, and LH": "",
  "Only the testes themselves": "",
  "Testosterone exerts negative feedback at both the hypothalamus (reducing GnRH pulse frequency) and the anterior pituitary (directly inhibiting FSH and LH release), creating a self-regulating loop that maintains testosterone levels within the normal physiological range.": "",
  "The LH surge that triggers ovulation is caused by:": "",
  "Rising progesterone from the corpus luteum": "",
  "Low FSH levels suppressing the pituitary": "",
  "Low estrogen levels from follicular decline": "",
  "High estrogen levels in the late follicular phase exerting positive feedback": "",
  "The LH surge is triggered by a unique positive feedback mechanism: when estrogen from the dominant follicle reaches a sustained high threshold level, it switches from inhibiting to stimulating the pituitary, causing a massive release of LH (and to a lesser extent FSH) that triggers ovulation approximately 24-36 hours later.": "",
  "GnRH must be released in a _____ pattern for normal reproductive function.": "",
  "Annual, seasonal": "",
  "Pulsatile (intermittent pulses)": "",
  "Random, unpredictable": "",
  "Continuous, steady": "",
  "GnRH must be released in a pulsatile fashion (approximately every 60-120 minutes) for normal FSH and LH secretion. Paradoxically, continuous GnRH administration actually suppresses gonadotropin release by downregulating pituitary GnRH receptors, a principle used therapeutically in GnRH agonist drugs.": "",
  "If pregnancy occurs, which hormone maintains the corpus luteum?": "",
  "Progesterone alone through autocrine signaling": "",
  "hCG (human chorionic gonadotropin) from the embryo": "",
  "LH from the pituitary": "",
  "FSH from the pituitary": "",
  "When pregnancy occurs, the implanting embryo's trophoblast produces hCG, which is structurally similar to LH and binds to the same receptors on the corpus luteum. This prevents the corpus luteum from degenerating, maintaining progesterone production until the placenta takes over hormone production around weeks 10-12.": "",
  "The placenta takes over hormone production from the corpus luteum at approximately:": "",
  "At the time of birth": "",
  "Week 30 of pregnancy": "",
  "Week 1 of pregnancy": "",
  "Week 10-12 of pregnancy": "",
  "By approximately weeks 10-12 of pregnancy, the placenta has developed sufficiently to produce its own progesterone and estrogen, making the corpus luteum no longer necessary. This transition is called the luteo-placental shift and ensures continued hormonal support for the pregnancy.": "",
  "Puberty is initiated by:": "",
  "Increased pulsatile GnRH secretion from the hypothalamus": "",
  "High testosterone levels present at birth": "",
  "Adrenal hormones alone": "",
  "Decreased body weight triggering hormone release": "",
  "Puberty begins when the hypothalamic GnRH pulse generator reactivates after childhood quiescence, increasing the frequency and amplitude of GnRH pulses. This stimulates the anterior pituitary to release increasing amounts of FSH and LH, which activate the gonads and initiate the development of secondary sex characteristics.": "",
  "What is GnRH (gonadotropin-releasing hormone)?": "",
  "A hormone produced by the ovaries that stimulates egg development": "",
  "A pituitary hormone that directly stimulates sperm production": "",
  "A hypothalamic hormone released in pulses that stimulates the anterior pituitary to secrete FSH and LH": "",
  "A gonadal hormone that provides negative feedback to the adrenal glands": "",
  "GnRH is a decapeptide hormone produced by the hypothalamus and released in a pulsatile fashion into the hypophyseal portal blood system. It is the master regulator of the reproductive axis, stimulating gonadotroph cells in the anterior pituitary to synthesize and secrete FSH and LH.": "",
  "What is the HPG axis?": "",
  "A hormonal pathway involving the heart, pancreas, and gallbladder": "",
  "A laboratory test measuring hormone levels": "",
  "A neural pathway connecting the hypothalamus to the spinal cord": "",
  "The hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis, the hormonal cascade that regulates reproductive function through feedback loops": "",
  "The HPG (hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal) axis is the hierarchical hormonal system that controls reproduction. The hypothalamus releases GnRH, the anterior pituitary releases FSH and LH, and the gonads produce sex hormones, with multiple negative (and one positive) feedback loops maintaining hormonal homeostasis.": "",
  "What does the term gonadotropin mean?": "",
  "A drug used to treat infertility": "",
  "A pituitary hormone that stimulates the gonads, specifically FSH and LH": "",
  "A hypothalamic hormone that inhibits reproductive function": "",
  "A hormone produced by the gonads themselves": "",
  "Gonadotropins are hormones that act on the gonads (ovaries and testes) to stimulate their function. The two main gonadotropins are FSH (follicle-stimulating hormone) and LH (luteinizing hormone), both produced by the anterior pituitary in response to GnRH stimulation.": "",
  "What is precocious puberty?": "",
  "Normal puberty occurring at the expected age": "",
  "Delayed onset of puberty after age 16": "",
  "A type of infertility diagnosed during puberty": "",
  "Abnormally early onset of puberty before age 8 in girls or age 9 in boys": "",
  "Precocious puberty is the abnormally early onset of sexual maturation, defined as before age 8 in girls or before age 9 in boys. It can be central (GnRH-dependent, from early HPG axis activation) or peripheral (GnRH-independent, from autonomous sex steroid production by gonads or adrenals).": "",
  "What is hypogonadism?": "",
  "Normal gonadal function during the aging process": "",
  "Enlargement of the gonads due to tumor growth": "",
  "Overproduction of sex hormones by the gonads": "",
  "Underactive gonads resulting in low sex hormone production, which can cause delayed puberty and infertility": "",
  "Hypogonadism refers to inadequate gonadal function resulting in low sex hormone production. Primary hypogonadism (hypergonadotropic) involves gonadal failure with elevated FSH/LH, while secondary hypogonadism (hypogonadotropic) involves hypothalamic or pituitary dysfunction with low FSH/LH.": "",
  "What does positive feedback mean in the context of the LH surge?": "",
  "LH directly stimulates more LH production from the pituitary": "",
  "Progesterone stimulates estrogen production in a reinforcing loop": "",
  "High estrogen levels amplify the pituitary's LH release rather than suppressing it, creating an escalating surge": "",
  "A hormone suppresses its own release to maintain homeostasis": "",
  "Positive feedback is a rare physiological mechanism where a hormone amplifies its own stimulus. In the menstrual cycle, when estrogen from the dominant follicle reaches a sustained high level, it switches from inhibiting to stimulating LH release, creating the dramatic LH surge that triggers ovulation.": "",
  "What does the term negative feedback mean in the HPG axis?": "",
  "FSH and LH always increase in response to rising gonadal hormones": "",
  "The hypothalamus produces hormones that directly destroy gonadal tissue": "",
  "Sex hormones produced by the gonads inhibit further hormone release from the hypothalamus and pituitary to maintain balance": "",
  "The gonads amplify hormone signals from the pituitary": "",
  "Negative feedback is the primary regulatory mechanism of the HPG axis. When sex hormones (testosterone, estrogen, progesterone) reach sufficient blood levels, they act on the hypothalamus and anterior pituitary to reduce GnRH, FSH, and LH secretion, preventing excessive hormone production and maintaining homeostasis.": "",
  "What is clomiphene?": "",
  "A selective estrogen receptor modulator (SERM) used as a fertility drug that blocks estrogen feedback to increase FSH/LH and stimulate ovulation": "",
  "An oral contraceptive that prevents ovulation by providing synthetic estrogen and progestin to suppress the mid-cycle LH surge from the anterior pituitary": "",
  "An injectable hormone used exclusively during in vitro fertilization procedures to stimulate multiple follicle development and synchronized oocyte maturation for retrieval": "",
  "A testosterone replacement therapy for men with hypogonadism that restores serum testosterone levels to the normal range and improves libido and muscle mass": "",
  "Clomiphene (Clomid) is a selective estrogen receptor modulator that blocks estrogen receptors at the hypothalamus and pituitary, tricking the brain into perceiving low estrogen. This removes negative feedback, causing increased GnRH, FSH, and LH secretion, which stimulates follicular development and ovulation in anovulatory women.": "",
  "What does inhibin do in the reproductive hormonal cascade?": "",
  "It selectively inhibits FSH release from the anterior pituitary through negative feedback": "",
  "It converts testosterone to estrogen in peripheral tissues": "",
  "It promotes LH secretion to trigger ovulation": "",
  "It stimulates GnRH release from the hypothalamus": "",
  "Inhibin is a glycoprotein hormone produced by Sertoli cells in males and granulosa cells in females that selectively suppresses FSH secretion from the anterior pituitary. This provides fine-tuned regulation of FSH independently of LH, helping to control the rate of gamete development.": "",
  "What is testosterone replacement therapy (TRT)?": "",
  "Medical administration of exogenous testosterone to men with hypogonadism who have low testosterone levels and symptoms": "",
  "A fertility treatment that increases sperm production": "",
  "An over-the-counter supplement for athletic performance": "",
  "A surgical procedure to restore testicular function": "",
  "Testosterone replacement therapy (TRT) is the medical administration of exogenous testosterone to men diagnosed with hypogonadism who have both low serum testosterone levels and clinical symptoms such as decreased libido, fatigue, reduced muscle mass, and depressed mood. It is a prescribed treatment that requires monitoring of hematocrit and PSA levels.": "",
  "A couple is struggling with infertility, and the woman's blood work on day 3 of her cycle shows FSH of 18 mIU/mL (normal < 10). Her physician explains this indicates diminished ovarian reserve. Why does a high day-3 FSH suggest poor ovarian function?": "",
  "FSH is elevated because progesterone from the corpus luteum is suppressing estrogen production": "",
  "High FSH means the ovaries are producing too many eggs, exhausting the follicle supply": "",
  "High FSH indicates a pituitary tumor that is overproducing gonadotropins": "",
  "The pituitary is secreting excess FSH because the ovaries are not producing enough estrogen and inhibin to provide negative feedback": "",
  "An elevated day-3 FSH reflects diminished ovarian reserve because the ovaries have fewer follicles and produce less estrogen and inhibin. Without adequate negative feedback, the pituitary compensates by increasing FSH secretion in an attempt to stimulate follicular growth, making high baseline FSH an indicator of declining fertility.": "",
  "A woman being treated for breast cancer is placed on a GnRH agonist (leuprolide) administered continuously. Her physician explains this will suppress her ovarian function. How does continuous GnRH administration paradoxically suppress reproduction when pulsatile GnRH stimulates it?": "",
  "Continuous GnRH stimulates the adrenal glands to produce cortisol, which suppresses reproduction": "",
  "Continuous GnRH directly destroys GnRH receptors permanently": "",
  "Continuous GnRH converts to an antagonist after 24 hours in the bloodstream": "",
  "Continuous GnRH causes initial stimulation but then downregulates pituitary GnRH receptors, suppressing FSH and LH secretion": "",
  "Continuous GnRH agonist administration initially causes a 'flare' of FSH and LH release, but sustained receptor stimulation leads to desensitization and downregulation of GnRH receptors on pituitary gonadotrophs. This effectively shuts down FSH and LH production, creating a 'medical castration' that suppresses estrogen production in hormone-sensitive cancers.": "",
  "An 8-year-old girl develops breast buds and pubic hair. Blood work shows elevated estradiol, LH, and FSH. A brain MRI is normal. Her pediatric endocrinologist diagnoses central precocious puberty. What is the underlying mechanism?": "",
  "The hypothalamic GnRH pulse generator has activated prematurely, driving early FSH, LH, and estrogen production through the normal HPG axis": "",
  "Exogenous estrogen exposure from environmental sources is causing the changes": "",
  "The adrenal glands are producing excess androgens that are converting to estrogen": "",
  "An ovarian tumor is autonomously producing estrogen independent of pituitary control": "",
  "Central (true) precocious puberty occurs when the hypothalamic GnRH pulse generator activates prematurely, driving the entire HPG axis to function as it would during normal puberty, but at an inappropriately early age. Elevated LH and FSH confirm central activation, distinguishing it from peripheral precocious puberty where gonadotropins would be suppressed.": "",
  "A 22-year-old female athlete with very low body fat has not had a menstrual period in 8 months. Her FSH, LH, and estrogen levels are all very low. What condition does this represent, and where is the dysfunction?": "",
  "PCOS with elevated androgens causing menstrual irregularity": "",
  "Functional hypothalamic amenorrhea caused by suppression of GnRH pulsatility from energy deficit and stress": "",
  "Primary ovarian failure with damaged ovaries unable to respond to gonadotropins": "",
  "Early menopause from genetic predisposition": "",
  "Functional hypothalamic amenorrhea occurs when the hypothalamic GnRH pulse generator is suppressed due to energy deficit, excessive exercise, psychological stress, or low body weight/fat. The low GnRH results in low FSH and LH, which leads to low estrogen and cessation of menstrual cycles. It is reversible with adequate nutrition and reduced exercise intensity.": "",
  "A man diagnosed with hypogonadism is started on testosterone replacement therapy. Six months later, he and his partner are trying to conceive but a semen analysis shows azoospermia (zero sperm). Why has TRT caused infertility?": "",
  "Exogenous testosterone directly kills existing sperm in the epididymis": "",
  "TRT causes irreversible atrophy of the seminiferous tubules": "",
  "Exogenous testosterone suppresses GnRH, FSH, and LH through negative feedback, shutting down intratesticular testosterone production and spermatogenesis": "",
  "Testosterone causes the vas deferens to become permanently blocked": "",
  "Exogenous testosterone suppresses the HPG axis through negative feedback, markedly reducing FSH and LH. Without FSH stimulation of Sertoli cells and without LH-driven intratesticular testosterone (which must be much higher than serum levels for spermatogenesis), sperm production ceases. This is an important counseling point for men of reproductive age considering TRT.": "",
  "A fertility clinic uses injectable hCG as part of an IVF protocol. The nurse administers hCG to trigger ovulation before egg retrieval. Why can hCG substitute for the natural LH surge?": "",
  "hCG is chemically identical to FSH and stimulates follicle growth": "",
  "hCG suppresses estrogen, which indirectly causes the follicle to rupture": "",
  "hCG is a form of progesterone that prepares the endometrium for implantation": "",
  "hCG is structurally similar to LH and binds to the same receptors, triggering the final maturation and release of oocytes": "",
  "hCG shares a common alpha subunit with LH and binds to the same LH/CG receptor on ovarian cells. This allows injectable hCG to mimic the natural LH surge, triggering the final maturation of oocytes and ovulation approximately 36 hours after administration, allowing precisely timed egg retrieval during IVF.": "",
  "A patient with endometriosis is prescribed a continuous combined oral contraceptive (without a placebo week) to manage her symptoms. The doctor explains this creates a state of pseudo-pregnancy. How does this hormonal therapy reduce endometriosis symptoms?": "",
  "It increases FSH to dissolve the endometrial implants": "",
  "Continuous synthetic estrogen and progesterone suppress ovulation and menstruation, reducing cyclical hormonal stimulation of ectopic endometrial tissue": "",
  "It causes immediate menopause which eliminates all endometrial tissue": "",
  "It stimulates ovulation which shrinks the endometrial implants": "",
  "Continuous combined oral contraceptives suppress the HPG axis through negative feedback, preventing ovulation and the cyclical rise and fall of estrogen and progesterone. Without these hormonal fluctuations, the ectopic endometrial implants receive less stimulation, reducing inflammation, pain, and the progression of endometriosis.": "",
  "A 50-year-old man visits his doctor complaining of low energy, decreased libido, and mood changes. Blood work shows total testosterone of 220 ng/dL (low), elevated LH, and elevated FSH. What type of hypogonadism does this pattern indicate?": "",
  "Normal age-related decline that does not require treatment": "",
  "Primary hypogonadism with the problem at the testes, since elevated LH/FSH shows the pituitary is trying to stimulate failing testes": "",
  "Androgen insensitivity syndrome": "",
  "Secondary (central) hypogonadism with the problem at the hypothalamus or pituitary": "",
  "Low testosterone with elevated LH and FSH indicates primary hypogonadism (hypergonadotropic hypogonadism), meaning the testes themselves are failing. The pituitary responds appropriately by increasing gonadotropin output to try to stimulate the underperforming testes. Causes include age-related Leydig cell decline, prior testicular injury, or Klinefelter syndrome.": "",
  "A pregnant woman at 8 weeks of gestation experiences sudden nausea and vomiting. Her obstetrician reassures her that this is likely related to a specific pregnancy hormone that peaks during the first trimester. Which hormone is most associated with morning sickness?": "",
  "Progesterone (produced by the corpus luteum of the ovary)": "",
  "Oxytocin (released by the posterior pituitary gland)": "",
  "Estrogen (produced by ovarian follicular granulosa cells)": "",
  "hCG (human chorionic gonadotropin)": "",
  "Morning sickness (nausea and vomiting of pregnancy) is most strongly correlated with rising hCG levels, which peak between weeks 8-12 of the first trimester. The nausea typically improves as hCG levels plateau and the placenta takes over hormone production, consistent with the temporal pattern of hCG secretion.": "",
  "A pediatric endocrinologist evaluates a 15-year-old boy who has not yet entered puberty. Blood work shows very low testosterone, low LH, and low FSH, but a GnRH stimulation test produces a robust rise in LH and FSH. What does this indicate about the location of the problem?": "",
  "The pituitary is unable to produce FSH and LH regardless of stimulation": "",
  "The testes are unable to respond to gonadotropins (primary hypogonadism)": "",
  "The hypothalamus is not producing GnRH adequately, but the pituitary and gonads can respond normally when stimulated": "",
  "The patient has androgen insensitivity syndrome with normal hormone levels": "",
  "A normal LH and FSH response to exogenous GnRH stimulation demonstrates that the anterior pituitary is functional and capable of producing gonadotropins. The low baseline gonadotropins therefore indicate the problem lies at the hypothalamic level, where insufficient GnRH production fails to activate the pituitary, a condition known as isolated hypogonadotropic hypogonadism (such as Kallmann syndrome).": ""
}